{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kendall_ver01/data/sn82014085/00393346863/1946051801/0254.xml":{"full_text":"Writ of Mandamus\nGranted to Sirica\nBooks, Records of W&terbury\nAmusements, Inc., To Be Inspected\nBy Applicant or Representative\nOpening*of all financial docks\nand records of the Waterbury\nAmusements, Inc., operator of the\nLklo Theater on South Main Street,\nto John D. Sirica, owner of a one\nquarter interest in the corporation,\nwas ordered in a Superior Court\nwrit of mandamus server last night\non AMra S. Quatrano, Frederick\nQuatrano and William A. Sirica, all\nofficers of the concern.\nThe mandamus proceedings were\nbrought yesterday before Judge Ed\nward J. Quinlan with the aid of\nAssistant State's Attorney Walter\nW. Smyth. The stockholder, in whose\nbehalf the state's attorney inter\nvened, was represented by Attorney\nEdward Mascolo.\nIn his complaint, Sirica stated\nthat on April 29 he asked the three\nofficers to give him an opportunity\nto examine the books, records,\nGuest Speaker\nROGER GLEASON\nBeth Israel\nClub to Hold\nFinal Meeting\nRogpr Gleason,\nF.B.I. Head, To\nBo Guest Speaker\nRoger Gleason, head of the P.B.I.\nin Connecticut, will be the guest\nspeaker at the final meeting of the\nBeth Israel Men\u2019s Club lor the sea\nson tomorrow morning in the ves\ntry rooms of the synagogue. Prior\nto the breakfast meeting, services\n\u25a0will be held at 9 A. M. President\nMurray L. Grossman will preside\nat the meeting.\nAn official troop charter will be\npresented to Troop 29, Boy Scouts,\nby Rabbi Seymour Gewirtz at the\nmeeting. Organized 30 years ago,\nthe troop, which is one of the old\nest in the city, is sponsored by the\nMen\u2019s Club. Rabbi Gewirtz will also\ndiscuss the progress oft the Water\nbury Jewish Federated Appeal Cam\npaign. Hie club\u2019s goal has been set\nat $60,000.\nMembers of the bowling league\nof the club will travel to New York\non June 2 to attend a baseball\ngame, Joseph Levine, president of\nthe league, announced. A banquet\nwill also be held. The club is now\nforming baseball and softball teams\nto play during the Summer.\nCity Parking\nSurvey Looms\nA central commtit*e to under\ntake the study of Waterbury\u2019s acute\nparking problems was formed yes\nterday at a meeting in the office\nof Frank Green, executive secretary\nof the Chamber of Commerce.\nJulius B. Smith was named chair\nman.\nThe committee is made up of\nmembers of the committees of the\nCity Plan Commission, Chamber of\nCommerce and the Merchants' Bu\nreau of the Chamber. A survey and\nstudy of the city\u2019s downtown park\ning situation will be made and re\nported to the Mayor.\nOther members of the central ex\necutive committee appointed were:\nJ. Warren Upson, secretary, Theo\ndore Scott-Smith, engineer, Frank\nE. Hess, representing the merch\nants and Joseph Wilhelm, repre\nseining tne manufacturers.\nRepresentatives of the three\nparking committees attending the\nmeeting at the Chamber of Com\nmerce were: Mayor John S. Mon\nagan, Julius B. Smith, Charles A.\nRoot, Richard P. Crane, Prank Pepe\nTheodore Scott- Smith, Wendell\nCross, Joseph Wilhelm, Frank E.\nHess, Ralph H. Paine, William\nV. Jones, B. Walker Bisset, Wil\nliam E. Van Tassel, J. Warren Up\nson and Prank J. Green.\nAuxiliary In\nSession Here\nMrs. John E. Hill, member of the\nNational Council of the Protestant\nEpiscopal Church, yesterday ad\ndressed the 05- annual business\nmeeting of the Connecticut branch\nof the Women\u2019s Auxiliary, Nation\nal Council of the Protestant Epis\ncopal Church. The meeting was\nheld at the Trinity Parish House,\nNew Haven.\nMorning session was opened with\nprayers by the Rev. C. Lawson Wil\nlard Jr., followed by the general\nbusiness meeting. Noonday pray\ners were led by the bishop coadjutor\nRt. Rev. Walter H. Gray. The bi\nshop of Connecticut, Rt. Rev. Fred\nerick G. Burlong, greeted the aux\niliary before lunch.\nTime Zoning Case\nPut Over One Week\nA one-week postponement was\nmade in Superior Court yesterday\non a scheduled hearing involving\nthe U. S. Time Corporation's zoning\ncase against the Mlddlebury Zoning\nCommission. The hearing will be on\na defendant\u2019s motion for correction\nof the concern's pleadings.\nchecks, receipts end ell records of\nfinancial operations, and to set a\ntime and place for the examination.\nThey refused the demand, the ap\nplication for the mandamus stated.\nThe mandamus, which was ap\nproved by the court, requires the\nthree officers to allow Sirica and\na public accountant to Inspect the\ncorporation\u2019s reoords and to allow\nSirica to take copies of the parts\nconcerning his interest.\nSirica, who stated that he owns\n11 shares of stock in the concern,\npointed out in his application that\nhe has no other adequate remedy\nat law expect through mandamus\nproceedings. The state\u2019s attorney\nstepped into the case, in accordance\nwith procedural requirements on\nmandamus applications.\nThe complaining stockholder\u2019s\napplication asked for examination\nof all books from the date of the\nformation of the corporation to\nApril 39\nWATERVILLE\nCorrespondent: Mrs. Gertrude\nLane; Telephone 3-0511.\nJune Bride\nParty Guest\nShirley Paradis\nTo Wad R. J. Lavoie\nWaterville, May IS Mrs. Louis\nBouldy and Mrs. Louis Tucker were\nhostesses recently at a greenback\nshower held at the Turf Banquet\nHall, in honor of their niece, Miss\nShirley Paradis, whose marriage to\nRomeo J. Lavoie will take place\nSaturday, June 8.\nTable decorations were carried\nout in gold ana green with a\nbridal cake forming the centerpiece.\nThe bride-to-be was presented with\na corsage of sweetpeas and daisies\nand harmonizing mlnature cor\nsages were dlnrlbuted to the guests.\nThe guests included: Mrs. Eugene\nO\u2019Connor, Mrs. Irving Tucker, Mrs.\nJack Tata, Mrs. Michael Callahan,\nMrs. Frank Tucker, Mrs. Edward\nConopask, Mrs. Delins Paradis, Mrs\nRaymond Paradis, Mrs. Harry Platt\nMrs. William Nolan, Mrs. Marjorie\nDillon, Mrs. Hermlne Bouley, Mrs.\nJoseph Bouldy, Mrs. Frank Martin,\nMrs. Fred MacLelland, Mrs. Kath\nerine Dahl, Mrs. Paul Fitzgerald,\nMrs. Arthur Blewitt, Jr., Mrs.\nCharles Katlluis, Mrs. Raymond\nMcGuire, Mrs. Alphonse Beaulieu,\nMrs. George Burgoyne, Mrs. Al\nphonse Carrette, Mrs. A1 Deslau\nriers, Mrs. Acland Wright, Mrs.\nWinifred Creaven, Mrs. Elizabeth\nDowney, Mrs. Michael Shlel, Mrs.\nWilliam Smith, Mrs. Mary Toner,\nMrs. Paul Donahlue, Mrs. Marie\nO\u2019Leary, Mrs. Frank Seery, Mrs.\nGeorge Goggln, Mrs. Harold Tucker\nMrs. Clarence Tucker, Mrs. Frank\nParadis, Mrs. Louis Tucker and Mrs\nLouis Bouley, Helen Wilson, Shirley\nBarnhardt, Ruth Tucker, Ethel\nStory, Shirley Paradis and Doris\nTucker.\nWilliam Creegan, Sr., of 1837\nThomaston Avenue is a patient at\nthe Waterbury Hospital.\nBrown-Rouskle\nThe marriage of Sherman Brown,\nson of Mr. and Mrs. Sherman\nBrown of Boyden Street and Miss\nMarguerite Joan Rouskie, daughter\nof Mr. and Mrs. Thomas J. Rousie,\nof New Britain, took place this\nmorning at 10 at the Church of St.\nJohn the Evangelist, New Britain.\nMrs. Raymond Malia, attended\nher sister as matron of honor and\nMr. Malia served as best man.\nHarold Brown, brother of the bride\ngroom, and Gerald Dwyer of New\nington, uncle of the bride, served as\nushers.\nFollowing are the church services\nfor tomorrow:\nUnion\u2014Worship Servire at 10;\nSunday School at 11 A. M. and\nEvangelistic service, 7:30 P. M.\nGospel Hall\u2014Breaking of Bread,\n10:30 A. M.; Sunday School at 8:30\nP. M.; and Gospel Service at 7:30\nP. M.\nThe Community Club will hold an\nOld-Fashioned Get-together to\nnight at 7:30 at Sprague gym.\nPrizes will be awarded for cards\nand dancing, and the door prize will\nbe Nylon stockings.\nTeen-Agers Dance\nFriday Draws 125\nThe dance sponsored by the\nKnights of Columbus in co-opera\ntion with the Mothers\u2019 Club of\nSS. Peter and Paul Church in An\nderson School gymnasium last night\nwas attended by more than 126\nteen-agers. Music was furnished\nfrom recordings and refreshment\nwas served.\nMrs. Albert Schiavone was in\ncharge of arrangements, assisted by\nMrs. Marcel Young, Mrs. Margaret\nBenner, Mrs. Lucile Blum, Mrs. Al\nfred Weihn and Mrs. Margaret\nKeaveney.\nCHANGE OF NAME\nPermission to change their sur\nname to Post was given by Superior\nCourt Judge Edward J. Quinlan yes\nterday to Stanley Poskavage, his\nwife, Anne, and Alfred Poskavage,\nall of Seymour.\nCatholic High School Choral Club Wins High Commendation\nOfficials of the State Music Fes-\ntlval held at Greenwich last week i\nhave announced the excellent rating\ngiven to the Waterbuyy Catholic\nHigh School Choral Club. The i\njudges cited particularly the \"beau\ntiful phrasing and melodic tone, the\naccuracy and fine diction, the per- i\nfeet quality of the ensemble.\u201d \"The j\nlovely, simple appearance of the\ngirls\u201d in their school uniforms was i\nalso commended. 1\nThe program, so well received at\nthe Greenwich auditions, including\nBortniansky's \u201cPater Noster,\u201d will 1\nbe repeated at the high school 1\nSpring Concert, on Sunday and\nMonday evenings, May 19 and 20, at\n8: IS. Other Choral Club selections i\nin the coming recital are \"Ma Little\nBanjo\u201d (Dichmont-Harrls) \u201cBells,\u201d t\n(Rachmaninoff), and \u201cThe Orches- i\ntra Song\u201d (Schuman). Smaller\nchoral groups will be featured in 1\nTosselU\u2019s Serenade,\u201d and Kreisler\u2019s\n\"Tribute to Our Mothers.\u201d In \u201cThe\nWorld Is Waiting For the Sunrise,\u201d j\n(Stelmetz) the group will be ac-\ncompanied by an instrumental en- 1\nManresa Band 1\nPlans Appeal J\nDinner To Open j\nMemorial Fund\nThe Waterbury Band. Mount j\nManresa Retreatants, completed\nplans for raising the Roger Walsh\nMemorial Fund at a meeting in the\nColumbus Club last ngiht.\nOpening the campaign will be a\ndinner meeting June 13. It will close\nuMfVi tRo QAth onnivorcorv HannilPt\nOctober 17.\nThe retreat band will raise a total\nof $3,000, which will go toward the\nbuilding of a $150,000 dormitory\nbuilding at the Jesuit Retreat\nHouse, Mount Manresa, Staten\nIsland. The local fund will honor\nthe memory of the late Roger v\nWlalsh, director of the band for 3\nover 30 years.\nThe captains heading the drive i\nare: Carl Demenske, Richard Ca- I\nrey. Martin Sullivstn, Edward 1\nCreem. John Mates, John Oreco,\nJohn Hartley, Nicholas 'Zappone,\nThomas Ashton and Frank Keefe.\nThe committee directing the\ndrive includes James Hennessy,\ngeneral chairman; Aurelio Greco,\nvice-chairman; Raymond O\u2019Neil,\nsecretary; James Barnett, treasur\ner; and Edward Creem, publicity.\n-v\nMaringola's\nSuit Settled\nA settlement out of court has\nbeen made in the $30,000 civil ac\ntion brought by Peter Maringola of\nWaterbury against James E. Conroy,\nMary S. Conroy, and George W.\nBowerman, all of Litchfield, as the\nresult of a cellar-stariway fall on\nthe defendants\u2019 property in Litch\nfield May 9, 1944.\nThe plaintiff, driver and delivery\nman for the Forest City Express\nCompany, claimed he was making\na delivery to the cellar when he\nstepped on an allegedly defective\nstair and fell. Back, chest, and\narm injuries, and a concussion of\nthe brain were listed in the com\nplaint.\nPapers withdrawing the suit have\nbeen filed in Superior Court.\nt:\n\nC\ns\nc\nS'\nh\nI\nE\ne\nI\nf\nc\n\u25a0V\nr\n\nc\nMountain Club\nMeets Tonight\nRonald Gower of Boston will give\nan illustrated lecture on Mt. Katah-\ndin and the surrounding country at i\na meeting of Connecticut Chapter,\nAppalachian Mountain Club, at the\nBunker Hill Church gymnasium to- i\nnight at 8. The meeting is open\nto all members of the church.\nMembers of the club will hold a\nhike starting at the Middlebury\nGreen this afternoon at 2:30. Mem\nbers will carry a picnic supper with\nthem and coffee and doughnuts will\nbe served by the committee in\ncharge. Members planning to par- i\nticipate in the hike are asked to\ncall Frank Gray at 4-3541.\nG.O.P. Women in\nMeeting Monday\nMrs. Viola B. Amelung, president\nhas announced the annual meeting\nof the Waterbury Women\u2019s Repub\nlican Club will take place Monday\nat 8 P. M. in the Colonial room\nof The Elton. Delegates will be\nappointed to attend the Young Re\npublicans\u2019 Convention in Hartford\nat the Hotel Garde, May 23 and 24.\nAfter the business meeting, the\nremainder of the evening will be\ncevoted to informal business and\nbridge.\nWoman Attacked\nOn Grove Street\nCharged with breach of the peace\nand assault, James Campbell, 21,\nof 154 Plaza Avenue, will be ar\nraigned in City Court today. Po\nlice reported that the youth is al\nleged to have attacked a 47-year\nold woman on Grove Street about\nmidnight.\nThe woman, Mrs. Julia Doyle of\n236 Circular Avenue, was reported\nto be in a fair condition today at\nSt. Mary\u2019s Hospital where she is\nbeing treated for a possible fracture\nof the right leg.\nCampbell was arrested by Patrol\nman Valmore Caron.\n1\nemble. The Cecilians a group of\nalented voice students, will sing\n\u25a0By the Waters of Minnetonka1\u2019\nLieurance) and \u201cEkh Lapti\u201d\nStone).\nSongs in costume will add visual\nharm to the musical evening. Eight\n;irls in old fashioned pale blue\nowns will recount muscially Novel\no's tale of \u2018The Little Damozel\u201d\nvho rejected all other suitors for\nhe blue-eyed page. The Colleens,\nfreshman group, appropriately\nIressed in dainty green will pres\nnt \u201cMy Irish Song of Songs,\u201d (Sul\n[van) a medley of old favorites.\nMilitary Feature Included\nThe concert will strike a military\ntote with choral club numbers,\nHymn to a Hero\u201d (Lovett-Waring)\nnd \u201cWhen Johnny Comes March\nig Home\u201d (Lambert-Wilhousky)\nnd in \"Marche Militaire\u201d (Schu\nert) by a piano ensemble.\nThe Waterbury Caholic High\nIchool orchesra will have a feaured\niart in the program. Under the dir\nction of Mr. Loro, it will present\nlerfurth\u2019s \u201cOverture\u201d and \u201cMexi\nhlaval Enrollee\nKilled in Theft\nBoston. May 18. (UP)\u2014A Rox\nury youth who soon was to have\nsined the Navy was shot to death\ny a policeman as he and a com\nanion fled after breaking into a\nranch library late last night. The\nompanion escaped.\nWilliam Munzert, Jr., 18, died at\nhospital of an abdominal wound\nlflicted by Patrolman Paul B.\nfurti6 of Roslindale. The police\nlan had been stationed inside the\ntoxbury branch of the Boston\n'ubllc Library because of a series\nf breaks there.\nCurtis reported that soon after\n1 P. M. a first floor window was\nbattered and two youth entered,\nie yelled for them to surrend#\nnd when they fled he fired two\nranting shots into the air. A third\nhot hit Munzert.\nBlind Vets\nFeted Here\nRed Gross Committee\nArranges Dance\nNovelty dances, a program of en\nirtainment and a community sing\nere featured last night at a dance\n>r 100 blind veterans from Avon\nlospital by the Camp and Hospital\nammittee of the Waterbury Chap\n:r, American Bed Cross, last night\nt the Waterbury Country Club.\nServing as hostesses were more\ntan 100 young women from the\ncovill Mfg. Co., Chase Brass Sc\nopper Co., the Bristol Company,\nouthern New England Telepone\no\u201e downtown insurance offices,\nores, and Pearl Street Neighbor\nood House.\nFeatured entertainers were June\nOwes of the Cliff McHale Studio;\n[artha McKnaught, a Chase \u00abm\nloye, Edith Moody, also a Chase\nmploye, and Virginia Gatling of\nearl Street Neighborhood House.\nDoughnuts, sandwiches and cof\n>e were served by the Red Cross\nanteen. In charge of arrangements\n'ere Mrs. Gordon Hurlbut, chair\nlan of the Camp and Hospital\nloifunittee, John Madden and Mrs.\nlertrude Swirda, both of the Sco\nill Mfg. Co. Arrangements for the\nlance were completed through\nourtesy of Scovill Mfg. Co. and\nhe Waterbury Country Club.\nOther members of the dance com\nnittee were Mrs. Leavenworth P.\n(perry. Miss Margaret Orr Benade,\nixecutive secretary of Waterbury\nChapter; Mrs. Ruth Little, Mts\n(udson Wells, Mrs. John Dye, Miss\ntachael Williams, Miss Betty White\nind Miss Evelyn Hallahan.\nFellowship\nPlay Scores\n\u2022Herbie\u2019s First Date,\u201d a play giver\nast night at the Bunker Hill Con\ngregational Church by members ol\nhe Junior High Pilgrim Fellowshlj\n>f the church, was attended by ovei\n100 persons.\nProceeds for the play and an old\n\u2019ashioned square dance which fol\nowed, will be used by the Mr. ant\niirs. Club, sponsors, for a forth\n:oming convention.\nIn the cast were: Priscilla Kirby\nNancy Mills, Marilyn Patterson\nCynthia Frederick and Judsoi\nVeils. Percy Knox was promptei\n\u2019or the square dance and music wai\n'urnished by Reggie Lawrence anc\nlis orchestra. Eleanor Mattsoi\nwas soloist.\nDu Bois Speaker\nIn Philadelphia\nSeveral members of the Indus\n;rial Foremen\u2019s Club of the Wa\n;erbury Y.M.CA. are registered ai\n;he annual meeting of the Nations\nCouncil of Foremen\u2019s Clubs ii\nPhiladelphia.\nC Arthur DuBois, chairman ol\n:he rating committee of the na\nional council, was scheduled t<\nspeak today on the rating program\nArvllle H. Stebbtns, another lo\n:al member, participated yea ter\nlay in a panel discussion on thi\nmbject, \"Building Strength Into i\nForemen\u2019s Club.\u201d\nOther Waterburians attendint\ninclude: Philip J. Rochon, John F\nFitzgerald, William H. Vining, Clar\nsnce a. Miller, and Arthur L. Pur\nin ton.\ncana\u201d and \u201cMelody In F.\" (Ruben\nstein). The piano duets, \u201cManana\u201d\n(Gould) and Grieg's \u201cBlano Con\ncerto\u201d will be played by Anne Bane,\nBarbara Bradley, Dorothy Flana\ngan and Katherine Panalltls.\nAlumnae members, Frances Kelly\n\u201943, harpist, and Teresa Hebert \u201946,\nvocal soloist will also be heard.\nMembers of the special choral\ngroups are Doris Dumalne, Rose\nmary Downs, Catherine D\u2019Amour\nand Paula Ruzzo, singing \u201cSere\nnade;\u201d Dolores Markus, Rita Rom\npre, and Elaine D\u2019Amour in Kreis\nler\u2019s \u201cTribute;\u201d Anne Kelly, Dor\nothea Cook Julia Nejame, Norma\nRuggiero, Alma Cyr, Janet Brown,\nClaire Lavigne and Grace Sclarra\nIn \u201cThe Liltle Damozel.\u201d Plano\nquartettes include Claire Lavigne,\nAnne Bane, Livia Sabia, Mary Jane\nPanalltls, Patricia Brophy, Dolores\nMarkus, Lucille Beausollel, Anne\nClarke, Diana Orsini, Norma Rug\ngiero, Anne Kelly and Mary Scully.\nChoral Club Members\nThe Choral Club Includes: Mar\nU.S.E.S. Finds\n575 Positions\nNumber of Jobless\nVeterans on Increase\nAbout 67S veterans have received\njobs through the U. S. Employment\nService here, Paul E. Parsons, man\nager of the Waterbury office, stated\nduring an Interview on the \u201cBrass\nCity Veteran\u201d program last night.\nThe main difficulty has been that\napplications far exceed the number\nof ooenlnirs. he said.\nAlso discussing the present em\nployment problem, Frank J. Green,\nsecretary of the Chamber of Com\nmerce, urged employers to register\nall job openings with the USES to\nspare veterans the discouragements\nof haphazard employment searches.\nWilliam C. McGowan, public rela\ntions representative of the Veterans\nAdvisory Center, 196 Grove Street,\nwas the program director.\nAt present Waterbury has 1,100\nunemployed veterans, Parsons re\nvealed. A press and radio job-de\nvelopment campaign has been star\nted by the USES to help combat this\nsituation. The USES is also meeting\nwith employers directly in an effort\nto solve the unemployment problem\nof servicemen. A classification pro\ncess for 'both jobs and veterans has\nbeen started which enables the right\nman to obtain the right job without\nlost motion for either employer or\nveteran, Parsons said.\nAbnormal unemployment will be\ngreatly decreased as soon as business\nhere becomes stabilised and produc\ntion increases in keeping with the\npresent high consumer demand.\nGreen stated during the broadcast.\nEdna Spallone\nSeeks Divorce\nDivorce actions were filed In\nSuperior Court today as follows:\nEphram J. Dupois of Waterbury\nagainst Josephine Donnelly Dupois\nof Brooklyn, N. Y.; married June\n18, 1026 in Brooklyn; cruelty since\nJan. 1, 1938 and Intemperance al\nleged; custody of six children\nsought.\nEdna Baker Spallone of Wolcott\nagainst Pasquale Spallone, also of\nWolcott; married Dec. 9, 1944;\ncruelty since Dec. 10, 1944 alleged;\nalimony sought.\n$63,000 Realty\nDeal Recorded\nMrs. Evelyn R. Margiotta, 591\nColumbia Boulevard Extension, has\npurchased the Hendricken Apart\nments at 317-326-327 North Main\nStreet and three smaller buildings\non Hendricken Place from Mary\nTV4Mr-i oVion nf Wa^AwVtumr a*i\u00abl PVior\nlotte and IRita Rhinehart of New\nRaven, according to a warranty\ndeed filed An the town clerk\u2019s office\nyesterday.\nThe approximate purchase price was\n$63,000. The property Includes four\nbuildings housing 30 tenants. A\n$35,000 mortage was taken out from\nthe Waterbury Trust Company by\nMrs. Margiotta. She also operates\nMark's Restaurant at 1577 Thom\naston Avenue.\nThe transaction was handled by\nAttorney Prank T. Healey and the\nMark A. Tierney real estate ageney\nVehicle Office\nClosed for Day\nThe branch office of the State\n{Motor Vehicle Department on Wa\ntertown Avenue was closed today In\ncompliance with a request by Gov\nernor Raymond E. Baldwin that all\nstate offices remain closed today In\nrespect to the late John M. Do we\nState controller and State Dem\nocratic chairman- Mr. Do we died\nWednesday. Euneral services wen\nheld today.\nMrs. Alice E. Bradley announced\nthe office will be open Monday\nduring the usual hours.\nUNHURT IN PtUNGE\nBoston, May li\u2014 (UP) -Three\nyear-okl Joan Bhrhorn plunged X\nfeet from a window of her home\nlanded, on a cement sidewalk anc\nthen picked herself up\u2014breathless\nscared but unhurt.\ngaret Wlthey, Patricia Deady,\nEunice Stokes, Doris Dumaine,\nMary Driscoll Patricia Cronan,\nJune St. Hilaire, Elaine Jacovlno,\nMary Walsh, Anne Bane, Nancy\nMullen, Helen Kennis, Norma Rug\ngiero, Rosemarie Cipriano, Joan\nMathieu, Anne Kelly, Dorothea\nCook, Ellen McGuire, Ann Ruoff,\nMarianne Pierce, Mary Scully, Mary\nAnn Rung. Eileen Kelly, Margaret\nCarroll, Arlene Hoar, Patricia Bro\nphy, Helen Dwyer, Patricia Wallace,\nEllen Unwin, Jean Quilter, Mary\nEllen Phelan, Betty Grant, Ann\nFlaherty, Dolores Markus, Dorothy\nFlanagan, Ann Martin, Elaine\nD\u2019Amour, Margaret Dunn, Rachel\nLorsmger, Marion Dumouchel, Rita\nRompre, Rosemary Cianciola, Joan\nAnderson, Rosemary Pekock, Jack\nlyn Healey, Mary Lou Dwyer, Mar\nion Johnson, Catherine Sugre, Bar\nbara Bradley, Marie Coffey, Marie\nHajjar, Madeline Della Bella,\nTheresa Mathiew, Clara D\u2019Angelo,\nLlvia Sabla, Catherine Lorusso, Pat\nricia Crean, Katherine Panilitis,\nMemorial Day\nPlans Ready\nMrs. Ann Schell, a member of\nthe Veterans\u2019 Memorial Day Com\nmittee announced last night 300\nWaterbury Gold Stair Mothers have\nbeen invited to attend a luncheon\nat The Elton May 30.\nReservations for guests other\nthan Gold Star Mothers must be\nmade with Mrs. Schell before\nThursday.\n\u2022Hie graves of Waterbury vet\nerans of all wars will be decorated\nby membeirs of the city\u2019s various\norganizations an Thursday and\nFriday.\nChairman of all Memorial Day\nsub-committees must make their\nfinal reports at the final meeting\nof the committee Friday night.\nWilliam Cahill, vice-chairman, said\nlast night, in order that the line\nof march for the parade ana plans\nfor other events can be announced.\nMr. Cahill presided at last night\u2019s\nmeeting in the absence of John\nFabiano, chairman.\nCor Theft\nSuit Basis\nTheft of a car owned by the\nDarcey Transportation Company\nfrom the Boiano Parking Station\non Spring Street is the basis of a\n$1,000 civil action filed in Common\nPleas Court today by the American\nAutomobile Fire Insurance Com\npany of Hartford against Salvatore\nBoiano, owner of the station.\nThe complaint states the car was\nIn the custody of the station own\ner at the time it was stolen, Jan.\n28. It had been parked there by\nHarry Russell, vice-president of the\nDarcey concern, the writ states.\nThe vehicle was later found in\nGreat Bend, Pa., in damaged condi\ntion.\nThe insurance company states it\nreimbursed Darcey for $1,410, and\nthat it cost $475 to rtpair the car.\nThe loss is computed at $660.\nDegree Conferred\nBy Auxiliary\nMias Catharine Wood, president,\npresided at a meeting of the Ladles\nAuxiliary of Canton T. R. Martin,\nNo. 8, I.O.OJF. in Odd Fellows Hall\nThursday night.\nMiss Lorella Newman vice-presi\ndent, read a report as a delegate to\nthe Department Association of\nLadies Auxiliaries, Patriot Millitant,\nI.O.O.F. of Connecticut which was\nheld recently in Hartford.\nThe mustering ceremonies were\nconfered on a class of candidates.\nMrs. Theodore Kurtz, Carl Peter\nson and J. O. Kanny sang during\nthe degree ceremonies.\nA reception was held in honor of\nMrs. Mabel Clark, president of the\ndepartment Association of Ladies\nAuxiliaries of Connecticut. Gifts\nwere presented to Mrs. Clark.\nMiss Wood was chairman of the\nentertainment program. Several\ndance numbers were presented by\nMiss Marion Nield of Thomas ton,\naccompanied by Mrs. Kurtz. Hazel\nIsieal rendered several vocal and\nguitar numbers.\nDistinguished guests attending\nwere Mr. and Mrs. George Rowell,\nMrs. Lillian Whitford, Col. Alfred\nLarson, Col. Harold Hanson and\nMrs. Hanson and Mrs. Clarabel\nDodson of Hartford; Ralph Foster\nof Ansonia and Harold Newman qf\nNaugatuck.\nA social hour was held with Miss\nWood hostess.\nHospital Bulletins\nRev. Peter Daly, pastor of the\nImmaculate Conception Church in\nNew Hartford, was admitted to St.\nMary\u2019s Hospital yesterday where he\nis undergoing observation. Father\nDaly was formerly stationed at St.\nMargaret\u2019s Church, this city.\nLIKE WOMEN\u2019S PURSES\nHollywood\u2014Mike Mazurki has no\npockets in the costume he wears in\nRKO Radio's Technicolor produc\ntion, \u201cSln/bad the Sailor,\" but in its\nballoon sleeves he carries a wallet,\noomb, a deck of pinochle cards, a\ngin rummy deck, a poker deck, three\nmurder mystery books, a box of ci\ngars, cigarettes, notebook, pen, pen\ncil and several letters his wife gave\nhim to mail a week ago.\nM\nRoma Gagner, Claire Mullen, Shir*\nley Belanger, Diana Oninl, Anne\n9amella, Anne Clark, Mary Foody,\nDoris Dinova, Rosemary Flanagan,\nRita Cravel, Mary Dowling, Mary\nNarus, Shirley Julian, Betsy Greene,\nMary Nolan, Dolores McEvoy Mad\neline Mark, Janet Bowen, Claire\nLavigne, Patricia Neagle, Irene\nDrevinskas, Patricia Delaney, Cor\nine Santa Lucia.\nOrchestra Personnel\nThe orchestra includes: Kath\narine Panalitls, Maureen Healey,\nJune St. Hilaire, Genevieve Sirica,\nAnn Slavin, Barbara Dressell, Mary\nJane French, Margaret Mulhall,\nMary Jane Panalitis, Phllis Mc\nMahon, Dorothy Birdsall Barbara\nCostello, {Claire Lavigne, Patricia\nWallace, Joan Lawlor, Patricia\nFeeley, Jeane Fagan, Maureen Car\nmody, Shirley Meskell, Patricia\nStrileckis, Arlayne Mellon, Barbara\nManzo, Blaine Purdy, Janet Bowen,\nAmila Walsh, Dorothy Flanagan,\nAnne Bane, Barbara Bradley Joan\nBlakeslee, Mary Scully, Patricia\nSullivan.\nStore Window\nFound Broken\nSuspect Held\nAttempt at House\n\u2018Break\u2019 Results hi\nFailure\nOne man was captured last night\nas he was in the process of bur\nglarizing the Fulton Market on\nWalnut Street, and would-be thieves\nin another Instance were fright\nened away police reported.\nMichael Farrell, 20, of 152 Oak\nStreet, caught in the act of at\ntempted burglary, will be arraigned\nin City Court today on charges of\nintoxication and breaking and en\ntering. Motor Patrolman John\nDeeley and Patrolman John Breen\nsaid the man entered the store after\nbreaking a large plate glass win\ndow in the front of the building.\nThey said when they arrived at\n9:50 P. M. they found potatoes\nstrewn over the floor.\nLt. John Galvin said nothing was\nf.a.lrgtn whan fhlavaa onnoraniflir Via rtf\non stealing from the home of En\nrico Belvedere of Connecticut Ave\nnue, were frightened away after\ntheir attempt to force a rear storm\nwindow failed.\nBEARDSLEY HONORED\nAttorney Harry J. Beardsley, state\npresident of the Society of the Sans\nof the American Revolution, was\nnamed Connecticut\u2019s representative\non the national board of trustees at\nthe 56th annual congress of the na\ntional society this week In Trenton,\nN. J.\nHoward E. Coe, delegate-at-large,\nand Mrs. Coe, were among Water\nbury residents at the convention.\nLate Realty\nNews\nDocuments filed at the town\nclerk\u2019s office in City Hall include.\nWarranty Deeds\nJ. Gray Somers to Lola Faye\nTroendly, property on Circuit Ave\nnue.\nPatrick F. Porto to Abraham\nand Bertha Abel, property on Chap\nman Avenue.\nPatrick A. McGuire to John F.\nand Hedwig c. Reymond, property\non Atwood Avenue.\nLouis and Viola M. Muchinsky to\nAnthony D. Greco, portion of prop\nerty recorded In Vol. 647, Fate M9,\nWaterbury Land Records.\nNora Griffin to The Murphy Ad\nvertising Co., property on Meriden\nRoad.\nCarmine and Anna Capuano to\nThe Murphy Advertising Co., prop\nerty on Meriden Road.\nEva T. and Rosa Herbet to Wil\nliam Yakubonis, property on Shef\nJules and Cecelia Bouraasa to\nWinston R. and Muriel E. Blllott,\nproperty on Hill Street.\nMortgage Deeds\nJohn F. and Hedwig C. Raymond\nto Ernest L. and Florla A. Reymond\nproperty on Atwood Avenue, $6,400.\nJohn Turek to Waterbury.\u2019 Sav\nings Bank, property on Jefferson\nand South Elm Streets, <6,500.\nAnthony D. Marro, and others,\nto The Waterbury Trust Co.' prop\nerty on East Main Street, <8,000.\nMichael Negro to Thomaston\nSavings Bank, property on South\nMain Street, <2,300.\nAssunta Crocco to Vinsenao Bi\nanchinl, property on Chatfleld Ave\nnue, $4,000.\nAssignment of Mortgages\nThe Lomas and Nettieton Com\npany to Wins ted Savings Bank, two\nmortgages.\nThe Waterbury National Bank to\nMrs. Anna C. Marro.\nMortgage Releases\nThe Prudential Insurance Com\npany, Newark, N. J., to Patrick A.\nMcGuire.\nFirst Federal' Savings 4k Loan\nAssociation of Waterbury to Julius\nand Margaret M. Budd.\nWaterbury Savings Bank to John\nTurek.\nThe Citiaens 4t Manufacturers\nNational Bank of Waterbury, trus\ntee under the will of Minnie B.\nCone, to Leo O. Devlin.\nMrs. Ann C. Marro to Anthony\nD. Marro and Dominick Clanciela\nThofnaston Savings Bank to Baas\nStoard\nInspections\nReduced by\nRainy Spell\n1,211 ten MmM\nTo teto at Freight\nStrati Lata\nThe testing lane set up by tlft\nPolice Department on Freight\nItreet Wednesday, was the subject\nif comment yesterday by William\nT. Hawkes, chairman of the Wa\nertoury Safety Council\nThe step taken by the Police\nDepartment, he said, should be\nllghly commended. He pointed out\nhat the Department is doing \u201ca\nrery good Job in this initial step,\nuid the Water bury Safety Coun\niil will back it every step of the\npray.\u201d\nMr. Hawkes urged support of the\nwfety campaign by local citizens\nmd asserted that any safety meas\nire would fail without such sup\nport.\nFor the first three days of the\nnspectian, Lt. Joseph Pettit said,\n1367 cars have passed through the\nane. He said that there was only\nslightly over 300 mrs inspected\nresterday, but he based the reduc\ntion on the ldblament weather.\nSix More Complete\nRed Cross Course\nMrs. Lester Greene, chairman o>\nthe Red Cross Home Service Corps,\nrvas announced that six additional\nrolunteer workers have completed a\nbasic training course, conducted by\nMiss Olice Walton, home service\nsecretary. They are: Mrs. Ted A.\nBerman, Mrs. John M. Brodie, Mrs.\nTalcott B. Clapp, Mrs. Herbert B\nDoe, Mrs. M. L. Vollmayer, and Miss\nSusan Smith.\nBattalion Dance\nTonight at Elton\nAbout 300 local members of the\n733d Field Artillery Battalion are\nexpected to attend a reunion dance\ntonight at The Elton. Thomas P.\nDowling is chairman of the dance\ncommittee for the Brass City Bat\ntalion. Music will be furnished by\nFrancis Delfino 